{
  "The theory of island biogeography predicts that species richness on an island is determined by:": "",
  "The balance between immigration rates and extinction rates, influenced by island size and distance from the mainland": "",
  "Only the temperature of the island when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Only the number of habitats on the island in most scenarios involving island factors": "",
  "Only the island's latitude, as conventional island theory would suggest": "",
  "MacArthur and Wilson's theory of island biogeography states that species richness on an island reflects a dynamic equilibrium between immigration (which adds species) and extinction (which removes them). Larger, closer islands have more species.": "",
  "According to island biogeography theory, which island would have the highest species diversity?": "",
  "A large island close to the mainland": "",
  "A small island close to the mainland": "",
  "A large island far from the mainland": "",
  "A small island far from the mainland": "",
  "Large islands near the mainland have the highest species diversity because large size supports more individuals (lower extinction) and proximity to the mainland increases immigration rates. Both factors promote higher species richness.": "",
  "Species richness generally increases as you move from:": "",
  "Low elevation to high elevation": "",
  "East to west": "",
  "The poles to the equator": "",
  "The equator to the poles": "",
  "The latitudinal diversity gradient shows that species richness increases from the poles toward the equator. Tropical regions have more species due to greater solar energy, longer evolutionary history, larger area, and higher productivity.": "",
  "Continental drift has influenced biogeography by:": "",
  "Only affecting aquatic organisms regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Keeping all organisms on one continent within the broader context of Continental analysis": "",
  "Separating and joining landmasses, creating barriers and corridors that influenced species distribution and evolution": "",
  "Having no effect on species distribution when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Continental drift has moved landmasses over millions of years, creating and eliminating geographic barriers. This has isolated populations (promoting speciation), connected previously separated biotas (allowing migration), and explains disjunct distributions of related organisms.": "",
  "The concept of a biome is based primarily on:": "",
  "The altitude of a region only": "",
  "The longitude of a region": "",
  "The species that live in an area": "",
  "The dominant climate, vegetation type, and abiotic conditions of a region": "",
  "Biomes are large-scale ecological regions characterized by their dominant climate, vegetation type, and abiotic conditions. The same biome (e.g., tropical rainforest) can occur on different continents with different species but similar ecological conditions.": "",
  "Dispersal of organisms to new areas can be limited by:": "",
  "Only biotic factors like predation": "",
  "Physical barriers like oceans, mountains, and deserts": "",
  "Having wings or other locomotion structures": "",
  "Proximity to other organisms of the same species": "",
  "Physical barriers such as large bodies of water, mountain ranges, and deserts limit the dispersal of many species. These barriers can isolate populations and contribute to biogeographic patterns and speciation.": "",
  "Endemic species are species that:": "",
  "Have been introduced to a new habitat by humans": "",
  "Are found everywhere on Earth": "",
  "Are found naturally only in a particular geographic area and nowhere else": "",
  "Are extinct": "",
  "Endemic species are found exclusively in a specific geographic region. Islands and isolated habitats often have high endemism because geographic isolation allows unique species to evolve. Madagascar's lemurs are a classic example.": "",
  "The species-area relationship predicts that:": "",
  "Smaller areas always have more species": "",
  "Area has no effect on species number": "",
  "Species number decreases as area increases": "",
  "Larger areas support more species, but the increase in species number slows with increasing area": "",
  "The species-area relationship (S = cAᶻ) shows that larger areas harbor more species, but the relationship is logarithmic: doubling the area does not double the number of species. This is fundamental to conservation biology and habitat preservation.": "",
  "Wallace's Line is a biogeographic boundary that separates:": "",
  "The Atlantic and Pacific oceans": "",
  "Africa and Europe": "",
  "The Asian and Australian fauna in Southeast Asia": "",
  "North and South America": "",
  "Wallace's Line runs through the Malay Archipelago and separates the fauna of Asia (placental mammals) from Australasia (marsupials and monotremes). It reflects deep water channels that prevented land bridges during ice ages.": "",
  "Climate change can affect biogeography by:": "",
  "Having no impact on species distributions": "",
  "Shifting species ranges toward the poles or to higher elevations as temperatures increase": "",
  "Making all habitats identical": "",
  "Only affecting marine organisms": "",
  "As global temperatures rise, species track suitable climate conditions by shifting their ranges poleward and upward in elevation. Species that cannot migrate fast enough or have nowhere to go face increased extinction risk.": "",
  "What is 'island biogeography'?": "",
  "The study of island geology and rock formations when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The process by which islands are formed by volcanic activity, as conventional island theory would suggest": "",
  "A theory that explains species richness on islands as a balance between immigration and extinction rates, influenced by island size and distance from the mainland": "",
  "The study of ocean currents around islands, particularly when island considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "Island biogeography theory, developed by MacArthur and Wilson, predicts that island species richness is determined by the equilibrium between immigration (higher for near islands) and extinction (lower for large islands).": "",
  "What does 'biogeographic realm' mean?": "",
  "A laboratory where biogeography experiments are conducted": "",
  "A single ecosystem within a larger biome": "",
  "The area controlled by a single predator species": "",
  "A large geographic region with a distinctive assemblage of plants and animals shaped by evolutionary and geological history": "",
  "Biogeographic realms (zoogeographic regions) are large geographic areas (e.g., Nearctic, Palearctic, Neotropical, Australasian) characterized by unique assemblages of organisms that reflect their shared evolutionary and geological history.": "",
  "What does 'endemic' mean in biogeography?": "",
  "A species that has been artificially introduced to an area": "",
  "A species that is found on every continent": "",
  "A species that causes disease in humans": "",
  "A species that is found naturally in one specific geographic area and nowhere else in the world": "",
  "Endemic species are native to and found exclusively in a particular region. Endemism is often high on islands and in isolated habitats. The Galapagos marine iguana, found only on the Galapagos Islands, is an example.": "",
  "What is a 'biome'?": "",
  "A group of species that migrate together when considering all relevant biome factors": "",
  "A single organism's habitat, as conventional biome theory would suggest": "",
  "A small, localized ecosystem, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A major regional community of organisms characterized by the dominant forms of plant life and the prevailing climate": "",
  "A biome is a large-scale ecological community type defined by its dominant vegetation and climate. Examples include tropical rainforest, desert, tundra, temperate grassland, and taiga. The same biome can occur on different continents.": "",
  "What does 'species-area relationship' mean?": "",
  "The correlation between a species' body size and its range": "",
  "The relationship between a species and its prey": "",
  "The concept that all species occupy the same area": "",
  "The ecological principle that larger geographic areas tend to support more species, though the increase slows with area": "",
  "The species-area relationship describes how the number of species increases with the area sampled, following a power function (S = cAᶻ). It is a key concept in conservation, predicting species loss from habitat reduction.": "",
  "What is 'dispersal' in biogeography?": "",
  "The genetic change within a population over time": "",
  "The process of decomposition": "",
  "The movement of organisms away from their area of origin to new areas, potentially expanding the species' range": "",
  "The extinction of a species from its native range": "",
  "Dispersal is the movement of individuals or their propagules (seeds, spores, larvae) from their place of origin to new locations. It is a fundamental process shaping species distributions and is influenced by physical barriers and organism mobility.": "",
  "What does 'latitudinal diversity gradient' mean?": "",
  "The uniform distribution of species across all latitudes": "",
  "The increase in diversity at high altitudes": "",
  "The decrease in diversity from east to west": "",
  "The pattern of increasing species diversity from the poles toward the equator": "",
  "The latitudinal diversity gradient is one of the most widely recognized patterns in ecology: species richness is highest near the equator and decreases toward the poles. This is attributed to greater energy, climate stability, area, and evolutionary time in tropical regions.": "",
  "What is 'vicariance'?": "",
  "The extinction of all populations of a species": "",
  "The merging of two previously separated populations": "",
  "The migration of a species to a new continent": "",
  "The separation of a continuously distributed ancestral population by the formation of a geographic barrier, leading to independent evolution": "",
  "Vicariance occurs when a geographic barrier (rising mountain, continental drift, river formation) splits a population's range. The separated populations then evolve independently, often leading to allopatric speciation.": "",
  "What is 'Gondwana'?": "",
  "An island in the Pacific Ocean given that prevailing Gondwana conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "A type of tropical biome, since the relevant Gondwana factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "An ancient southern supercontinent that included South America, Africa, Antarctica, Australia, and India before their separation by continental drift": "",
  "A modern continent in the Northern Hemisphere, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Gondwana was an ancient southern supercontinent that began breaking apart about 180 million years ago. Its fragmentation explains the distribution of related organisms on now-separated continents, such as ratite birds and marsupials.": "",
  "What does 'range' mean for a species in biogeography?": "",
  "The number of different foods a species eats": "",
  "The total geographic area over which a species is found in nature": "",
  "The distance an individual organism travels in a day": "",
  "The temperature range an organism can tolerate": "",
  "A species' range is the geographic area where it naturally occurs. Range is determined by historical factors (dispersal, vicariance), ecological requirements, and physical barriers. Species ranges can expand or contract over time.": "",
  "The Hawaiian Islands are home to over 50 species of honeycreeper birds, all descended from a single ancestral finch species that colonized the islands millions of years ago. Some have curved beaks for nectar, others have thick beaks for seeds, and still others have pointed beaks for insects. How does island biogeography help explain this diversity?": "",
  "Each species was independently created on each island": "",
  "Gene flow between islands prevented any speciation": "",
  "All honeycreepers evolved on the mainland and then migrated to Hawaii": "",
  "Geographic isolation between islands reduced gene flow, and diverse ecological niches promoted adaptive radiation from the founding species": "",
  "Island biogeography explains this through colonization of an isolated archipelago followed by adaptive radiation. Geographic isolation between islands limited gene flow, and the diversity of available ecological niches drove the evolution of diverse beak forms from a single ancestor.": "",
  "Ratite birds (ostriches in Africa, emus in Australia, rheas in South America, and kiwis in New Zealand) are flightless birds found on different continents. Despite being unable to fly, their DNA shows they are closely related. What biogeographic explanation best accounts for their distribution?": "",
  "They were transported by humans to different continents": "",
  "They all flew to their current locations before losing the ability to fly": "",
  "They evolved independently on each continent through convergent evolution": "",
  "Their common ancestor lived on Gondwana, and the breakup of the supercontinent through continental drift separated the populations, which then evolved independently": "",
  "The distribution of ratites is best explained by vicariance. Their common ancestor lived on Gondwana when it was a single landmass. As Gondwana fragmented over millions of years, populations were carried to different continents, where they evolved independently into distinct species.": "",
  "A conservation biologist is designing a nature reserve to protect the maximum number of species. Based on island biogeography theory, which reserve design would likely protect the most species?": "",
  "One large, connected reserve rather than several small, isolated ones": "",
  "Reserve size does not matter for species conservation": "",
  "Several small, isolated reserves totaling the same area as one large reserve": "",
  "Many tiny reserves spread across the landscape": "",
  "Island biogeography theory predicts that a single large reserve will support more species than several small ones of equal total area (the SLOSS debate generally favors large). Larger reserves have lower extinction rates, more habitat diversity, and can support viable populations of large-ranging species.": "",
  "Researchers compare two islands equidistant from the mainland. Island A is 100 km² and has 50 bird species. Island B is 10 km² and has 20 bird species. Both have been surveyed for the same duration. Which ecological principle explains the difference?": "",
  "Island A has a higher immigration rate because it is larger": "",
  "Island B has fewer species because its climate is different": "",
  "The species-area relationship: larger islands support more species due to greater habitat diversity and larger populations that resist extinction": "",
  "The competitive exclusion principle": "",
  "The species-area relationship predicts that larger areas support more species. Island A's larger area provides more habitats, supports larger populations (reducing extinction risk), and has a larger target for colonizing species, all contributing to higher species richness.": "",
  "As climate change causes average temperatures to rise, alpine plant species in mountain ecosystems are observed to shift their ranges to higher elevations. A student predicts that species already at the mountain summit will simply move higher. Why is this prediction problematic?": "",
  "Temperature does not affect plant distribution in mountains": "",
  "Species at mountain summits have nowhere higher to go and face extinction as their habitat shrinks to nothing": "",
  "Alpine plants can easily adapt to any temperature": "",
  "All mountain species will benefit from warmer temperatures": "",
  "Summit species face a 'summit trap' or 'escalator to extinction.' As temperature zones shift upward, habitat area decreases (mountains narrow at the top) and eventually disappears at the peak. Species that cannot disperse to other mountains face extinction.": "",
  "Madagascar, an island off the southeast coast of Africa, is home to lemurs, which are found nowhere else on Earth. However, Madagascar lacks the monkeys and apes found in mainland Africa. What biogeographic concept explains this pattern?": "",
  "Lemurs evolved on the African mainland and then swam to Madagascar": "",
  "Lemurs and monkeys are the same group of animals": "",
  "Madagascar separated from Africa before monkeys and apes evolved; the ancestors of lemurs colonized the island early and evolved in isolation, creating many endemic species": "",
  "Monkeys outcompeted lemurs on Madagascar and then went extinct": "",
  "Madagascar separated from Africa approximately 160 million years ago and from India about 88 million years ago. Early primate ancestors (lemur ancestors) colonized the island before more derived primates evolved on the mainland. In isolation, lemurs underwent adaptive radiation, producing many endemic species.": "",
  "A researcher notices that tropical rainforests in South America, Africa, and Southeast Asia contain different species but have remarkably similar ecological structures (tall canopy trees, epiphytes, diverse insects, large predatory cats). What biogeographic concept explains this similarity across different continents?": "",
  "All tropical species evolved from a single common ancestor that lived on all three continents simultaneously": "",
  "There is no real similarity between these forests": "",
  "Similar climatic conditions across tropical regions produced similar biomes through convergent ecological evolution, even though the species are different": "",
  "Species migrated between all three continents recently": "",
  "The biome concept explains this: similar climatic conditions (temperature, precipitation) produce similar ecological structures regardless of which species are present. Different species on different continents have convergently evolved to fill similar ecological roles in similar climatic regimes.": "",
  "A habitat corridor connecting two nature reserves separated by farmland is proposed. Using island biogeography principles, predict how this corridor would affect the species in the reserves.": "",
  "The corridor would increase extinction rates by spreading diseases": "",
  "The corridor would increase effective habitat area and immigration between reserves, increasing species diversity and population viability in both": "",
  "The corridor would have no effect on species in the reserves": "",
  "The corridor would cause all species to leave the reserves": "",
  "Wildlife corridors function like reducing the distance between islands. They increase immigration between reserves (bringing new species and genetic diversity), reduce extinction risk by allowing population movement and recolonization, and effectively increase the connected habitat area.": "",
  "After a volcanic eruption creates a new island in the Pacific Ocean, ecologists observe colonization over decades. The first arrivals are windblown spiders and insects, then seabirds, then plants whose seeds arrive via birds. Eventually, species richness levels off. What does this leveling off represent in island biogeography theory?": "",
  "No more organisms can physically reach the island": "",
  "The island has reached a dynamic equilibrium where the rate of new species immigration equals the rate of species extinction": "",
  "The island's ecosystem has stopped changing entirely": "",
  "All possible species on Earth have colonized the island": "",
  "The species richness equilibrium on an island is a dynamic balance. Immigration rate decreases as more species accumulate (fewer new species can arrive), while extinction rate increases (more species means more competition). When the two rates are equal, species richness stabilizes.": "",
  "Scientists observe that the flora and fauna of Australia are remarkably different from those of nearby Southeast Asian islands (across Wallace's Line). Australia has marsupials (kangaroos, koalas) while Southeast Asia has placental mammals (tigers, elephants). What explains this sharp biogeographic boundary?": "",
  "Deep ocean channels between the landmasses prevented terrestrial mammal dispersal, and Australia's long isolation after separating from Gondwana allowed marsupials to diversify without competition from placentals": "",
  "Placental mammals evolved from marsupials but only on Asian islands, since the prevailing theory about Australia would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "Climate differences between the regions caused different species to evolve without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Humans introduced different animals to each region when the interaction between Australia and Asian factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Wallace's Line marks deep ocean channels that persisted even during ice age sea level drops, preventing land bridges. Australia separated from Gondwana and remained isolated for tens of millions of years, allowing marsupials to diversify. Placental mammals that dominated on the Asian mainland could not cross these water barriers.": ""
}